# Why Replacing Works

Many people think replacing loses information, but it doesn't.

Compare these two tails for a subsequence of length 2:

```text
[5, 6]
```

and

```text
[1, 4]
```

Both represent an increasing subsequence of length 2, but `[1, 4]` is better because a smaller ending value makes it easier to extend with future numbers.

The algorithm only needs the **length** of the LIS, not the actual subsequence.

---

# Complexity Comparison

| Approach                    | Time Complexity | Space Complexity |
| --------------------------- | --------------- | ---------------- |
| Brute Force (Recursion)     | **O(2ⁿ)**       | **O(n)**         |
| DP (Nested Loops)           | **O(n²)**       | **O(n)**         |
| Binary Search LIS (Optimal) | **O(n log n)**  | **O(n)**         |

---

# Important Takeaways

* The minimum deletions problem is directly transformed into an LIS problem.
* **Formula:** `Minimum Deletions = n - LIS Length`.
* Brute force checks all subsequences and is exponential.
* Dynamic programming computes the LIS ending at each index in `O(n²)`.
* The optimal solution maintains the smallest possible tails of increasing subsequences and uses binary search to achieve `O(n log n)`, meeting the expected complexity.
